  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD069892",
      "title": "Proteomics Analysis of Human Mesenchymal Stromal/Stem Cell Sarcomagenesis Model Identifies ALDH1A3 and CD99 as Potential Targets in the Transformation Process",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Mesenchymal stromal/stem cells (MSC) may represent the cell-of-origin for sarcoma development. A collection of human MSCs sequentially mutated with an increasing number of oncogenic hits served to recreate a step-wise process of sarcomagenesis. To identify potential protein targets of interest in the MSC-sarcoma transformation process, quantitative mass spectrometry based (LC-MS/MS) proteomics was performed. Among the proteins hits identified as significantly regulated in the transformation process ALDH1A3 and CD99 were selected and further studied. Both ALDH1A3 abundance levels and activity were significantly up-regulated in early phase (immortalized) and fully transformed (sarcoma forming) cells as compared to normal MSCs. Inversely, CD99 total protein and cell-surface abundance levels were down-regulated in immortalized and transformed MSCs. Down-regulated CD99 was also identified in several human bone and soft tissue sarcoma subtypes. Proteomics investigation of a MSC-transformation model of sarcoma has yielded ALDH1A3 and CD99 as potential targets for sarcomagenesis that may contribute to a greater understanding of the disease and the development of novel therapeutic approaches.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "Bone marrow\u2013derived human mesenchymal stem cell (BM-hMSC) cultures, including wild-type (hBM#44, hBM12A, hBM15A, hBM#7043, hBM#7083, hBM#8004) and genetically modified derivatives (MSC-3H, MSC-4H, MSC-5H, and their FUS-CHOP\u2013overexpressing counterparts), were maintained in DMEM supplemented with 15% MSC-screened fetal bovine serum under 5% CO\u2082 at 37 \u00b0C. Cells were harvested at 80\u201390% confluence and lysed in 100 mM triethylammonium bicarbonate (TEAB) containing 1% SDS according to the TMT 10-plex Mass Tag Labeling kit protocol (Thermo Scientific, cat.#90113). Lysates were incubated for 30 min at 4 \u00b0C with end-over-end rotation, followed by brief centrifugation (1000 rpm, 30 s). Supernatants were sonicated at 30% amplitude (3 \u00d7 10 s pulses with 30 s intervals on ice) and clarified by centrifugation (14,000 \u00d7 g, 5 min, 4 \u00b0C). Protein concentrations were determined using the Pierce BCA assay (Thermo Scientific, cat.#23227). Lysates were aliquoted into Protein LoBind tubes and stored at \u221280 \u00b0C until labeling.   For TMT labeling, 100 \u00b5g of protein per sample was reduced, alkylated, and digested with trypsin, followed by labeling with TMT 10-plex reagents according to manufacturer\u2019s instructions with minor modifications. After labeling, samples were pooled and desalted prior to LC-MS/MS analysis. Peptides were separated on an EASY-nLC 1000 system using a 25 cm \u00d7 75 \u00b5m C18 column (2 \u00b5m particle size) coupled to an Orbitrap Fusion Lumos Tribrid mass spectrometer. Mobile phase A was 0.1% formic acid in water, and mobile phase B was 0.1% formic acid in acetonitrile. Peptides were eluted with a linear gradient from 5\u201325% B over 112 min, 25\u201360% B over 20 min, and 60\u201390% B over 5 min prior to MS analysis.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Raw MS data were processed in Proteome Discoverer v2.0 (Thermo Fisher Scientific) using the SEQUEST search algorithm against the UniProt Swiss-Prot human database. Searches allowed up to two missed cleavages with a precursor mass tolerance of 10 ppm and fragment mass tolerance of 0.6 Da. Static modifications included carbamidomethylation of cysteine and TMT 10-plex labeling of lysine residues and peptide N-termini. Dynamic modifications included methionine oxidation and deamidation of asparagine and glutamine.   Peptide-spectrum matches were filtered to achieve a false discovery rate (FDR) < 1% using the Percolator node. Quantification was performed at the MS\u00b3 level using synchronous precursor selection (SPS) with up to 10 MS\u00b2 fragments per cycle. Peak integration was carried out with a \u00b110 ppm window, and reporter ion intensities were corrected for isotopic impurities according to the manufacturer\u2019s specifications. Data were normalized across TMT channels within Proteome Discoverer to account for sample loading differences. Protein abundance ratios were calculated based on unique and razor peptides with high confidence assignments.",
